# Fluff Date: 2026-02-16 11:04:06
overview:<p>The Peacekeeper is a 25-ton SecurityMech designed by Coventry Metal Works as the original namesake of the company's long-running Peacekeeper series. Introduced within a decade of the SecurityMech Treaty of 2613's multilateral ratification, it was among the first designs built explicitly to the treaty's standards. Powered by a fusion engine and armed with weapons rivaling its Commando cousin, the Peacekeeper pushed the boundaries of what a SecurityMech could be. However, the market ultimately judged this "gold-standard" SecurityMech as too powerful for genuine police work yet too weak for front-line military duty, leaving it stranded between two roles. The subsequent development of the downgraded Copper—the "copper-standard" model—eclipsed the original, though the Peacekeeper remained in production at Coventry for centuries as a premium option for security forces willing to pay for its capabilities.</p>

capabilities:<p>The Peacekeeper is built on an IndustrialMech chassis but powered by a fusion engine, giving it performance characteristics that blur the line between SecurityMech and true BattleMech. It features environmental sealing, allowing pilots to operate freely in contaminated environments or when deploying chemical agents—a significant advantage over the unsealed Copper. Heavy armor provides protection approaching that of a light BattleMech, making the design more survivable than most SecurityMechs in hostile situations.</p><p>The armament consists of two medium lasers in the right arm, an SRM-2 in the right torso, and a single machine gun in the left arm, all guided by an advanced fire control system. A front-mounted searchlight supports night operations. This weapons suite gives the Peacekeeper genuine combat capability against armored targets, but it proved to be a double-edged sword commercially. The fusion engine and heavier armament drove costs well above the Copper's price point, while the design still lacked the speed, armor, and firepower to compete with purpose-built military 'Mechs. This awkward positioning between civilian and military markets ultimately limited the Peacekeeper's commercial success, though its robust design and superior environmental protection retained a loyal following among premium security operators.</p>

deployment:<p>The sole production model of the Peacekeeper, the PK-6 mounts two medium lasers, an SRM-2, and a machine gun guided by advanced fire control, with environmental sealing and a front-mounted searchlight. This configuration represents Coventry Metal Works' original vision for a premium SecurityMech that could handle genuine military threats, though the market ultimately deemed it overbuilt for police work. The PK-6 remained in continuous production at Coventry alongside the more popular Copper line, serving as the foundation from which both the Copper and the later Peacemaker would evolve.</p>

history:<p>The Peacekeeper holds a unique place in SecurityMech history as the design that launched Coventry Metal Works' entire Peacekeeper series and demonstrated both the promise and limitations of the SecurityMech concept. Developed shortly after the SecurityMech Treaty of 2613 established the legal framework for armed IndustrialMechs in police service, the Peacekeeper was engineered as a serious security platform that could handle threats beyond the capacity of conventional law enforcement.</p><p>In practice, the market proved unkind to the Peacekeeper's ambitions. Police forces and corporate security agencies found the fusion-powered design expensive to purchase and maintain, while its armament—though impressive for a SecurityMech—fell far short of what military commanders expected from a 'Mech. The design became what critics called a "paper tiger," capable on paper but filling no practical niche effectively. Coventry Metal Works recognized this commercial reality and developed the CPK-19 Copper as a stripped-down alternative, which quickly overtook the Peacekeeper in sales and became the series' true flagship.</p><p>Despite its commercial disappointment, the Peacekeeper remained in production at Coventry for centuries, serving customers who valued its fusion power plant, environmental sealing, and heavier armament. The design's most significant legacy proved to be the license that Irian Technologies later negotiated for the Peacekeeper's blueprints, using them as the basis for the revolutionary Peacemaker PoliceMech. In this way, the Peacekeeper's fusion-powered architecture found new life in a design that finally solved the market positioning problem that had plagued the original.</p>

